%S A219037 2,6,66,73786976294838206466
%N A219037 Numbers k such that k divides 2^k + 2 and (k-1) divides 2^k + 1.
%C A219037 Also, numbers k such that 2^k == k-2 (mod k*(k-1)).
%C A219037 The sequence is infinite: if m is in this sequence, then so is 2^m + 2.
%C A219037 No other terms below 10^20.
%D A219037 W. Sierpinski, 250 Problems in Elementary Number Theory. New York: American Elsevier, 1970. Problem #18.
%H A219037 Kin Y. Li et al., <a href="http://www.math.ust.hk/excalibur/v14_n2.pdf">Solution to Problem 323</a>, Mathematical Excalibur 14(2), 2009, p. 3.
%F A219037 Conjecture: a(n+1) = 2^a(n) + 2 for all n.
%Y A219037 Intersection of A006517 and A055685.
%Y A219037 Cf. A217468, A216822, A171959.
